{"type":"text","timestamp":1780373171677,"sessionID":"ses_1797e0d22ffeXZXWmRS3UmbrPG","part":{"id":"prt_e86829f1b001WghkL2NhwOGC0N","messageID":"msg_e86828e45001lFw5iqRCpN7qUL","sessionID":"ses_1797e0d22ffeXZXWmRS3UmbrPG","type":"text","text":"The existing reports confirm D4 is not part of the live-remediated aggregate and the only saved D4 ablation is the pre-remediation two-scenario run. I’ll inspect the playbook scenario definitions to propose a measurable routine-task instrument and a concrete third scenario from authored coverage gaps.","time":{"start":1780373167899,"end":1780373171675},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0fa816e44a8d16c4016a1e56afe0dc81918a5c991ba9918392","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780373171740,"sessionID":"ses_1797e0d22ffeXZXWmRS3UmbrPG","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Ela8QqKFr9YxUFHXBIjV7Bsr","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/README.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/README.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"sk-code Skill-Benchmark Artifacts\"\n3: description: \"Benchmark inputs and reports for sk-code, scored by the deep-improvement Lane C harness in router and live modes.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"sk-code benchmark\"\n6:   - \"skill-benchmark artifacts\"\n7:   - \"sk-code routing benchmark\"\n8: ---\n9: \n10: # sk-code Skill-Benchmark Artifacts\n11: \n12: > Reports and inputs for benchmarking how well `sk-code` is routed, discovered, and used in practice, kept beside the skill they measure.\n13: \n14: ---\n15: \n16: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n17: \n18: The deep-improvement Lane C harness benchmarks `sk-code` against its own `manual_testing_playbook` scenarios across five dimensions (D1 routing, D2 discovery, D3 efficiency, D4 usefulness, D5 connectivity). This folder holds the run inputs and the dual reports each run writes.\n19: \n20: Two trace modes score the same playbook corpus:\n21: \n22: - **router** is deterministic and offline. It replays the machine-readable router in `sk-code/references/smart_routing.md`. This is the CI gate.\n23: - **live** dispatches each scenario through `cli-opencode` to a real model and grades the model's stated routing plus observed activation. This is the operator default for a true routing verdict.\n24: \n25: ### Key Statistics\n26: \n27: | Metric | Value |\n28: |---|---|\n29: | Corpus | sk-code `manual_testing_playbook` (24 scenarios: 15 routing, 2 advisor, 7 browser) |\n30: | Trace modes | router (deterministic CI gate), live (real dispatch) |\n31: | Latest router verdict | FAIL, aggregate 40 |\n32: | Latest live verdict | CONDITIONAL, aggregate 71 |\n33: | D4 usefulness (approximate) | about 49 |\n34: \n35: ### How This Compares\n36: \n37: | Tool | Checks | Use When |\n38: |---|---|---|\n39: | This benchmark | Whether the skill is routed, discovered, and useful in practice | Measuring real routing quality |\n40: | `validate.sh` | Document shape and required sections | Checking spec-folder structure |\n41: | `manual_testing_playbook` | Described behavior per scenario | Authoring or hand-running scenarios |\n42: \n43: ---\n44: \n45: ## 2. QUICK START\n46: \n47: Run from the repository root.\n48: \n49: Router mode (deterministic, no network):\n50: \n51: ```bash\n52: node .opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs \\\n53:   --mode=skill-benchmark --skill=sk-code \\\n54:   --outputs-dir=.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/router-final \\\n55:   --trace-mode=router\n56: ```\n57: \n58: Live mode (dispatches through cli-opencode, needs a configured provider):\n59: \n60: ```bash\n61: SKILL_BENCH_OPENCODE_MODEL=openai/gpt-5.5-fast SKILL_BENCH_OPENCODE_VARIANT=high \\\n62: node .opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs \\\n63:   --mode=skill-benchmark --skill=sk-code \\\n64:   --outputs-dir=.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-final \\\n65:   --trace-mode=live --advisor-mode=python \\\n66:   --scenarios=SD-001,LS-001,CS-001,RD-002,MR-001\n67: ```\n68: \n69: Expected result: a `verdict=` line on stdout plus `skill-benchmark-report.json` and `skill-benchmark-report.md` in the outputs dir.\n70: \n71: ---\n72: \n73: ## 3. STRUCTURE\n74: \n75: ```text\n76: benchmark/\n77: +-- router-final/      # Current deterministic run (router mode)\n78: +-- live-final/        # Current live run (cli-opencode) + d4-ablation.json\n79: +-- baseline/          # Frozen pre-optimization snapshot, do not regenerate\n80: +-- after/ full/ live/ # Earlier development runs, superseded by the -final pair\n81: `-- fixtures/sk-code/   # Legacy synthetic fixtures, superseded by the playbook corpus\n82: ```\n83: \n84: | Path | Purpose |\n85: |---|---|\n86: | `router-final/` | Latest router-mode report (real-gold scoring, the CI gate) |\n87: | `live-final/` | Latest live-mode report plus `d4-ablation.json` (skill-on vs skill-off usefulness) |\n88: | `baseline/` | First sk-code run, kept as a before-snapshot, not reproducible |\n89: | `fixtures/sk-code/` | Two legacy fixtures, no longer the default corpus |\n90: \n91: ---\n92: \n93: ## 4. READING THE REPORTS\n94: \n95: Each run writes a matched pair:\n96: \n97: | File | Content |\n98: |---|---|\n99: | `skill-benchmark-report.json` | Machine report: verdict, D1 to D5, funnel, ranked bottlenecks, scenario rows |\n100: | `skill-benchmark-report.md` | The same report rendered for reading, generated from the JSON to avoid drift |\n101: | `d4-ablation.json` | Usefulness deltas per scenario (skill-on score, skill-off score), stamped approximate |\n102: \n103: Start with the `.md` file for the verdict and the ranked bottlenecks. Open the `.json` file for per-scenario detail.\n104: \n105: ---\n106: \n107: ## 5. TROUBLESHOOTING\n108: \n109: | What you see | Cause | Fix |\n110: |---|---|---|\n111: | Live dispatch returns null after about 4 minutes | `xhigh` reasoning variant is too slow per dispatch | Set `SKILL_BENCH_OPENCODE_VARIANT=high` |\n112: | `provider/model not found` or 401 in live mode | The provider is not configured | Run `opencode providers list`, then log in to the provider you name in `SKILL_BENCH_OPENCODE_MODEL` |\n113: | Browser scenarios skip with `SKIP-NO-BROWSER` | `bdg` (Chrome) is unavailable | Install `bdg`, or accept the honest skip for non-Chrome legs |\n114: | Router mode reports orphan references | A routable doc is not reachable from the router | Add it to `RESOURCE_MAP` or the always-loaded default in `smart_routing.md` |\n115: \n116: ---\n117: \n118: ## 6. RELATED RESOURCES\n119: \n120: ### Related Skills\n121: \n122: | Skill | Relationship | Use When |\n123: |---|---|---|\n124: | [`deep-improvement`](../../deep-improvement/SKILL.md) | Owns the Lane C benchmark harness | Running or extending the benchmark |\n125: | [`sk-code`](../SKILL.md) | The skill under measurement | Reading or tuning the router being scored |\n126: \n127: ### Related Documents\n128: \n129: | Document | Purpose |\n130: |---|---|\n131: | [`smart_routing.md`](../references/smart_routing.md) | The machine-readable router the benchmark replays |\n132: | [`start-skill-benchmark-loop`](../../../commands/deep/start-skill-benchmark-loop.md) | The command that drives a benchmark run |\n\n(End of file - total 132 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"sk-code Skill-Benchmark Artifacts\"\ndescription: \"Benchmark inputs and reports for sk-code, scored by the deep-improvement Lane C harness in router and live modes.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"sk-code benchmark\"\n  - \"skill-benchmark artifacts\"\n  - \"sk-code routing benchmark\"\n---\n\n# sk-code Skill-Benchmark Artifacts\n\n> Reports and inputs for benchmarking how well `sk-code` is routed, discovered, and used in practice, kept beside the skill they measure.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nThe deep-improvement Lane C harness benchmarks `sk-code` against its own `manual_testing_playbook` scenarios across five dimensions (D1 routing, D2 discovery, D3 efficiency, D4 usefulness, D5 connectivity). This folder holds the run inputs and the dual reports each run writes.\n\nTwo trace modes score the same playbook corpus:","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/README.md","time":{"start":1780373171732,"end":1780373171739}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0fa816e44a8d16c4016a1e56b39b988191a94ad9b7b0a4c43d"}},"id":"prt_e8682ae07001mTFCvvvCFieL9J","sessionID":"ses_1797e0d22ffeXZXWmRS3UmbrPG","messageID":"msg_e86828e45001lFw5iqRCpN7qUL"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780373171757,"sessionID":"ses_1797e0d22ffeXZXWmRS3UmbrPG","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_cChxIaKnY9Ro2qB79tcoHlSs","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/references/smart_routing.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/references/smart_routing.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Smart Router - Routing Logic and Resource Maps\n3: description: Authoritative routing logic for sk-code's surface-based routing — intent classification, surface-to-resource maps for WEBFLOW + OPENCODE + MOTION_DEV, load tiers, verification commands, and UNKNOWN fallback.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Smart Router - Routing Logic and Resource Maps\n7: \n8: Authoritative routing reference for sk-code. Consolidates intent classification + resource loading into the single Barter-style smart-routing entry point. Detection logic lives in [`stack_detection.md`](./stack_detection.md); phase lifecycle lives in [`phase_detection.md`](./phase_detection.md).\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n13: \n14: ### Purpose\n15: \n16: The smart router maps a detected surface (WEBFLOW / OPENCODE / UNKNOWN) plus a classified intent (IMPLEMENTATION / DEBUGGING / VERIFICATION / etc.) to the exact references, assets, and verification commands needed for the active task. Loads only the smallest relevant set so the active context window stays focused.\n17: \n18: ### When to Use\n19: \n20: - After surface detection (see [`stack_detection.md`](./stack_detection.md)) determines WEBFLOW / OPENCODE / UNKNOWN\n21: - When classifying task wording into the dominant work intent\n22: - When mapping intent to concrete reference paths\n23: - When picking verification commands for the surface\n24: \n25: ### Core Principle\n26: \n27: Routing is a two-stage decision: **surface-first, intent-second**. Surface narrows the resource family (Webflow vs OpenCode vs UNKNOWN); intent narrows the specific files within that family. Motion.dev resources are a **peer category** loaded after either surface, not a third surface.\n28: \n29: ### Key Sources\n30: \n31: - [`stack_detection.md`](./stack_detection.md) — surface detection (WEBFLOW/OPENCODE/UNKNOWN) and OpenCode language sub-detection\n32: - [`phase_detection.md`](./phase_detection.md) — Phase 1/2/3 lifecycle and phase-specific resource expectations\n33: - `SKILL.md` §2 SMART ROUTING — operator-facing summary of this routing contract\n34: \n35: ---\n36: \n37: ## 2. INTENT MODEL\n38: \n39: Intent classification scores task text against weighted keyword signals to pick the dominant work type after surface detection.\n40: \n41: | Intent | Strong Signals |\n42: | --- | --- |\n43: | IMPLEMENTATION | `implement`, `build`, `create`, `feature`, `component`, `script`, `module` |\n44: | CODE_QUALITY | `lint`, `format`, `quality gate`, `p0`, `p1`, `style`, `naming`, `standards` |\n45: | DEBUGGING | `debug`, `fix`, `bug`, `error`, `broken`, `failing`, `stack trace`, `console error` |\n46: | VERIFICATION | `verify`, `done`, `complete`, `works`, `fixed`, `passing`, `build`, `type-check` |\n47: | TESTING | `test`, `unit`, `integration`, `coverage`, `vitest`, `pytest`, `shellcheck` |\n48: | DEPLOYMENT | `deploy`, `cdn`, `wrangler`, `release`, `metadata`, `skill graph` |\n49: | PERFORMANCE | `lighthouse`, `lcp`, `tbt`, `inp`, `cls`, `pagespeed`, `performance` |\n50: | ANIMATION | `animation`, `motion`, `transition`, `gsap`, `lenis`, `swiper` |\n51: | MOTION_DEV | `motion.dev`, `motion-dev`, `motion_dev`, `Motion API`, `animate()`, `inView`, `scroll()`, `stagger`, `cross-stack animation` |\n52: | FORMS | `form`, `validation`, `filepond`, `schema`, `zod` |\n53: | VIDEO | `hls`, `video`, `stream`, `player` |\n54: | HOOKS | `hook`, `session-prime`, `user-prompt-submit`, `pre-tool-use`, `post-tool-use` |\n55: | CONFIG | `json`, `jsonc`, `schema`, `descriptor`, `config` |\n56: | LANGUAGE_STANDARDS | `typescript`, `python`, `shell`, `commonjs`, `strict`, `docstring` |\n57: \n58: ### Scoring algorithm\n59: \n60: 1. Sum weighted keyword hits from the request, target files, and known task context.\n61: 2. Boost explicit phase signals (verification, debugging, testing, code quality) by +5 when the phase is unambiguous.\n62: 3. Select the top intent.\n63: 4. Select a second intent when the score delta to the next intent is small (`AMBIGUITY_DELTA = 1`).\n64: 5. For OPENCODE surface, run language sub-detection after intent selection.\n65: \n66: ### Doc-only edit anti-signals\n67: \n68: Doc-only prose changes subtract from `sk-code` intent scoring and add to `sk-doc` scoring, even when the target file is under `.opencode/skills/`.\n69: \n70: | Prompt signal | Effect |\n71: | --- | --- |\n72: | `update headline`, `rewrite headline`, `headline section` | `sk-code -2`, `sk-doc +3` |\n73: | `clarify description`, `clarify the X model`, `documentation section` | `sk-code -2`, `sk-doc +3` |\n74: | `add a one-line summary`, `add summary at the top` | `sk-code -2`, `sk-doc +3` |\n75: | `improve readme`, `reorganize readme`, `rewrite section` | `sk-code -2`, `sk-doc +3` |\n76: | `SKILL.md` or `README.md` plus prose-only verbs | `sk-code -2`, `sk-doc +3` |\n77: \n78: Do not apply this anti-signal when the same request asks to modify executable code, parser logic, tests, shell behavior, TypeScript/Python entrypoints, JSON schema behavior, or routing algorithms. In that case, keep OPENCODE surface detection and load `sk-code`.\n79: \n80: Multi-symptom prompts like `fix Webflow animation flicker` should load both DEBUGGING and ANIMATION. Prompts like `update TypeScript advisor fixture` should load OPENCODE plus LANGUAGE_STANDARDS and CODE_QUALITY.\n81: \n82: Motion.dev API or decision prompts should load MOTION_DEV as a resource intent. If the target files are Webflow files, keep the surface as WEBFLOW and add `references/motion_dev/` for cross-stack API/decision context; if the target is `.opencode/`, keep the surface as OPENCODE and load Motion only as reference material.\n83: \n84: ### Surface-specific intent notes\n85: \n86: - **WEBFLOW** intent scoring favors browser/runtime terms, animation, forms, video, performance, deployment, and verification.\n87: - **MOTION_DEV** intent scoring favors Motion API, timeline, scroll/gesture, performance, import-mode, snippet, and decision_matrix terms; it supplements the detected surface rather than replacing it.\n88: - **OPENCODE** intent scoring favors language standards, hooks, config, scripts, advisor/tests, metadata, and alignment verification.\n89: - Unsupported surfaces stay UNKNOWN even if intent scoring is strong.\n90: \n91: ---\n92: \n93: ## 3. LOAD TIERS\n94: \n95: | Tier | When | Resources |\n96: | --- | --- | --- |\n97: | ALWAYS | Every invocation | Universal code quality + error recovery from `references/universal/` |\n98: | SURFACE | After WEBFLOW/OPENCODE detection | Surface-specific shared resources (`webflow/shared/*` or `opencode/shared/*`) |\n99: | INTENT | After intent classification | Implementation, debugging, verification, performance, etc. matching the top-1 intent (and top-2 when ambiguous) |\n100: | LANGUAGE | OPENCODE only | JavaScript, TypeScript, Python, Shell, Config standards from the matching `opencode/<lang>/*` folder |\n101: | ON_DEMAND | Explicit deep-dive keywords | Extended checklists and niche references (e.g. `webflow/css/patterns.md` for advanced CSS patterns) |\n102: \n103: ---\n104: \n105: ## 4. WEBFLOW MAP\n106: \n107: WEBFLOW loads from `references/webflow/` and `assets/webflow/`. The per-language sub-tree (`webflow/{javascript,css,html,shared}/`) and topical workflow dirs (`webflow/{implementation,debugging,verification,performance,deployment}/`) coexist; the router selects across both.\n108: \n109: | Intent | Resources |\n110: | --- | --- |\n111: | IMPLEMENTATION | MUST load the implementation trio: `references/webflow/implementation/animation_workflows.md`, `references/webflow/implementation/implementation_workflows.md`, `references/webflow/implementation/performance_patterns.md`; then add per-language style guides (`webflow/javascript/style_guide.md`, `webflow/css/style_guide.md`) and focused guides such as forms/vendor refs as needed |\n112: | CODE_QUALITY | `assets/webflow/checklists/code_quality_checklist.md`, `webflow/javascript/quality_standards.md`, `webflow/css/quality_standards.md`, `webflow/shared/enforcement.md` |\n113: | DEBUGGING | `references/webflow/debugging/*`, `webflow/shared/dev_workflow.md`, universal debugging checklist |\n114: | VERIFICATION | `references/webflow/verification/verification_workflows.md`, `webflow/shared/enforcement.md`, verification checklist |\n115: | PERFORMANCE | `references/webflow/performance/cwv_remediation.md`, `references/webflow/performance/resource_loading.md`, `references/webflow/performance/interaction_gated_loading.md`, `webflow/css/quality_standards.md` (will-change, GPU props), `webflow/javascript/quality_standards.md` (RAF, debounce) |\n116: | DEPLOYMENT | `references/webflow/deployment/cdn_deployment.md`, `references/webflow/deployment/minification_guide.md`, `references/webflow/deployment/webflow_staging_production.md` |\n117: \n118: ### Implementation trio contract\n119: \n120: Any WEBFLOW surface detection MUST load the implementation trio before intent-specific expansion:\n121: \n122: - `references/webflow/implementation/animation_workflows.md`\n123: - `references/webflow/implementation/implementation_workflows.md`\n124: - `references/webflow/implementation/performance_patterns.md`\n125: \n126: This is a contract, not a guideline. It prevents SD-001-style partial coverage where the surface is correct but implementation guidance falls below the expected threshold.\n127: \n128: ### Per-language overlay\n129: \n130: After WEBFLOW + intent selection, also load the language overlay matching the changed/target file extensions:\n131: \n132: | Target language | Overlay resources |\n133: | --- | --- |\n134: | JavaScript (`.js`) | `webflow/javascript/{style_guide,quality_standards,quick_reference}.md`, `webflow/shared/cross_language_rules.md` |\n135: | CSS (`.css`) | `webflow/css/{style_guide,quality_standards,quick_reference,patterns}.md`, `webflow/shared/cross_language_rules.md` |\n136: | HTML (`.html`) | `webflow/html/{style_guide,quality_standards}.md`, `webflow/shared/cross_language_rules.md` |\n137: | Mixed (CSS + JS in same task) | Both per-language sets above |\n138: \n139: ---\n140: \n141: ## 5. MOTION_DEV MAP\n142: \n143: MOTION_DEV loads from `references/motion_dev/` and `assets/motion_dev/` as a peer resource category. It is not a separate code surface; it supplements WEBFLOW, OPENCODE, or future surfaces when the request needs Motion API, integration, or decision guidance.\n144: \n145: | Intent | Resources |\n146: | --- | --- |\n147: | ANIMATION / MOTION_DEV | `references/motion_dev/quick_start.md`, `references/motion_dev/animate_and_timelines.md`, `references/motion_dev/scroll_and_gestures.md` |\n148: | PERFORMANCE | `references/motion_dev/performance_and_pitfalls.md` |\n149: | IMPLEMENTATION / API | `references/motion_dev/integration_patterns.md`, exact snippet assets such as `assets/motion_dev/snippets/animate_on_scroll.js` and `assets/motion_dev/snippets/in_view_reveal.js` |\n150: | CODE_QUALITY / DECISION | `references/motion_dev/decision_matrix.md`, `assets/motion_dev/install_card.md` |\n151: | TESTING / PLAYBOOK | `assets/motion_dev/playbook_entries.md` plus manual testing playbook Motion scenarios |\n152: \n153: When WEBFLOW and MOTION_DEV both match, load Webflow guidance for CDN, `window.Motion`, Designer, and browser verification constraints, then load `motion_dev/` for cross-stack Motion details.\n154: \n155: When explicit non-Webflow language and MOTION_DEV both match, do not load `references/webflow/*` or `assets/webflow/*`. Load Motion.dev peer resources by exact path while keeping the surface UNKNOWN or N/A:\n156: \n157: - `references/motion_dev/quick_start.md`\n158: - `references/motion_dev/integration_patterns.md`\n159: - `references/motion_dev/decision_matrix.md`\n160: - `references/motion_dev/performance_and_pitfalls.md`\n161: - `references/motion_dev/animate_and_timelines.md`\n162: - `references/motion_dev/scroll_and_gestures.md`\n163: - exact snippet assets under `assets/motion_dev/snippets/` when the prompt asks for examples\n164: \n165: Do not emit directory placeholders such as `references/motion_dev/`, `assets/motion_dev/snippets/`, or `references/webflow/` in playbook result YAML. Name the exact canonical files.\n166: \n167: ### Performance and decision contracts\n168: \n169: PERFORMANCE intent with Motion.dev or Webflow animation MUST name these canonical files when relevant:\n170: \n171: - `references/motion_dev/performance_and_pitfalls.md`\n172: - `references/webflow/performance/cwv_remediation.md`\n173: - `references/webflow/performance/resource_loading.md`\n174: \n175: DECISION intent MUST name:\n176: \n177: - `references/motion_dev/decision_matrix.md`\n178: - `references/webflow/implementation/animation_workflows.md` when comparing Motion.dev against Webflow-owned animation patterns\n179: - `references/webflow/implementation/performance_patterns.md` when the decision depends on performance constraints\n180: \n181: ---\n182: \n183: ## 6. OPENCODE MAP\n184: \n185: OPENCODE loads from `references/opencode/` and `assets/opencode/`.\n186: \n187: ### Always-load (every OPENCODE invocation)\n188: \n189: - `references/opencode/shared/universal_patterns.md`\n190: - `references/opencode/shared/code_organization.md`\n191: \n192: ### Intent overlay\n193: \n194: | Intent | Resources |\n195: | --- | --- |\n196: | CODE_QUALITY | `assets/opencode/checklists/universal_checklist.md` plus the language-matching checklist |\n197: | VERIFICATION | `references/opencode/shared/alignment_verification_automation.md`, `assets/scripts/verify_alignment_drift.py` |\n198: | HOOKS | `references/opencode/shared/hooks.md` |\n199: | CONFIG | `references/opencode/config/*` |\n200: | LANGUAGE_STANDARDS | Detected language folder's `quick_reference.md`, `style_guide.md`, `quality_standards.md` |\n201: \n202: ### Language overlay\n203: \n204: | Language | Resources |\n205: | --- | --- |\n206: | JAVASCRIPT | `references/opencode/javascript/{style_guide,quality_standards,quick_reference}.md`, `assets/opencode/checklists/javascript_checklist.md` |\n207: | TYPESCRIPT | `references/opencode/typescript/{style_guide,quality_standards,quick_reference}.md`, `assets/opencode/checklists/typescript_checklist.md` |\n208: | PYTHON | `references/opencode/python/{style_guide,quality_standards,quick_reference}.md`, `assets/opencode/checklists/python_checklist.md` |\n209: | SHELL | `references/opencode/shell/{style_guide,quality_standards,quick_reference}.md`, `assets/opencode/checklists/shell_checklist.md` |\n210: | CONFIG | `references/opencode/config/{style_guide,quality_standards,quick_reference}.md`, `assets/opencode/checklists/config_checklist.md` |\n211: \n212: ### Authoring checklist gating\n213: \n214: When OPENCODE intent is `authoring-new-X`, additionally load the matching authoring checklist:\n215: \n216: | Authoring target | Checklist |\n217: | --- | --- |\n218: | New skill | `assets/opencode/checklists/skill_authoring.md` |\n219: | New agent | `assets/opencode/checklists/agent_authoring.md` |\n220: | New command | `assets/opencode/checklists/command_authoring.md` |\n221: | New MCP server | `assets/opencode/checklists/mcp_server_authoring.md` |\n222: | Spec folder write | `assets/opencode/checklists/spec_folder_authoring.md` + `assets/opencode/recipes/spec_folder_write.md` |\n223: \n224: ---\n225: \n226: ## 7. VERIFICATION COMMANDS\n227: \n228: | Surface | Required verification evidence |\n229: | --- | --- |\n230: | WEBFLOW | `node .opencode/skills/sk-code/assets/webflow/scripts/minify-webflow.mjs`; `node .opencode/skills/sk-code/assets/webflow/scripts/verify-minification.mjs`; `node .opencode/skills/sk-code/assets/webflow/scripts/test-minified-runtime.mjs`; plus desktop/mobile browser console clean evidence when runtime behavior changes |\n231: | OPENCODE | `python3 .opencode/skills/sk-code/assets/scripts/verify_alignment_drift.py --root <changed-scope>`; plus targeted language/project tests such as vitest, pytest, shellcheck, JSON validation, or spec validation for changed spec folders |\n232: | UNKNOWN | User-selected verification command set before completion claim |\n233: \n234: ---\n235: \n236: ## 8. UNKNOWN FALLBACK\n237: \n238: If no supported surface matches, ask:\n239: \n240: 1. Is this Webflow/frontend code or `.opencode/` system code?\n241: 2. Which files or directories are changing?\n242: 3. Which verification command proves the claim?\n243: 4. Should a new `sk-code` route be planned before implementation?\n244: \n245: Do not load Go/NextJS/React Native resources from canonical sk-code; those surfaces live in the Barter sk-code fork (`barter/.opencode/skills/sk-code/references/`). Canonical sk-code only owns WEBFLOW + OPENCODE + MOTION_DEV.\n246: \n247: ### UNKNOWN fallback checklist\n248: \n249: Returned when intent confidence is low (`max(intent_scores) < 0.5`) OR when the user explicitly asks for stack-agnostic guidance:\n250: \n251: - Confirm the active runtime surface (WEBFLOW or OPENCODE)\n252: - Confirm the task intent (implementation / debugging / verification / etc.)\n253: - Provide one concrete input, error, or expected output\n254: - Confirm the verification command set before completion\n255: \n256: ---\n257: \n258: ## 9. LOADING DISCIPLINE (DO / DON'T)\n259: \n260: ### DO\n\n(Showing lines 1-260 of 459. Use offset=261 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Smart Router - Routing Logic and Resource Maps\ndescription: Authoritative routing logic for sk-code's surface-based routing — intent classification, surface-to-resource maps for WEBFLOW + OPENCODE + MOTION_DEV, load tiers, verification commands, and UNKNOWN fallback.\n---\n\n# Smart Router - Routing Logic and Resource Maps\n\nAuthoritative routing reference for sk-code. Consolidates intent classification + resource loading into the single Barter-style smart-routing entry point. Detection logic lives in [`stack_detection.md`](./stack_detection.md); phase lifecycle lives in [`phase_detection.md`](./phase_detection.md).\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nThe smart router maps a detected surface (WEBFLOW / OPENCODE / UNKNOWN) plus a classified intent (IMPLEMENTATION / DEBUGGING / VERIFICATION / etc.) to the exact references, assets, and verification commands needed for the active task. Loads only the smallest relevant set so the active context window stays focused.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- After surface detection (see [`stack_detection.md`](./stack_detection.md)) determines WEBFLOW / OPENCODE / UNKNOWN","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-code/references/smart_routing.md","time":{"start":1780373171751,"end":1780373171756}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0fa816e44a8d16c4016a1e56b39ba081918be9b38e66155b32"}},"id":"prt_e8682ae24001xNKaDWf2GYzpNF","sessionID":"ses_1797e0d22ffeXZXWmRS3UmbrPG","messageID":"msg_e86828e45001lFw5iqRCpN7qUL"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780373171774,"sessionID":"ses_1797e0d22ffeXZXWmRS3UmbrPG","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_mouEaIpkGz76AlCcIcNddyt3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: #!/usr/bin/env node\n2: 'use strict';\n3: \n4: /**\n5:  * router-replay.cjs — Mode A deterministic in-skill smart-router replay.\n6:  *\n7:  * The converged design needs the intra-skill router replayed deterministically\n8:  * (zero leakage, CI-friendly) as the D1-intra signal and the D2 discovery proxy.\n9:  * The router lives as INTENT_SIGNALS + RESOURCE_MAP inside a fenced block in the\n10:  * target SKILL.md; it is documentation, not an importable module, so this script\n11:  * extracts the dictionaries and reproduces the exact substring-scoring semantics:\n12:  * lowercase the task, score each intent by whether each keyword is a substring,\n13:  * keep intents within an ambiguity delta of the top score, then union the default\n14:  * resource + RESOURCE_MAP[intent] for the selected intents.\n15:  *\n16:  * Exit: 0 on a successful replay (even with zero intents), 2 on unparseable router.\n17:  */\n18: \n19: const fs = require('fs');\n20: const path = require('path');\n21: \n22: const AMBIGUITY_DELTA = 1; // mirror the in-skill router: keep near-tied intents\n23: \n24: function readSkillMd(skillRoot) {\n25:   const p = path.join(skillRoot, 'SKILL.md');\n26:   if (!fs.existsSync(p)) throw new Error(`SKILL.md not found under ${skillRoot}`);\n27:   return fs.readFileSync(p, 'utf8');\n28: }\n29: \n30: // Pull the {...}-balanced body that follows `NAME = {` from the SKILL.md text.\n31: function extractDictBody(text, name) {\n32:   const start = text.indexOf(`${name} = {`);\n33:   if (start === -1) return null;\n34:   let i = text.indexOf('{', start);\n35:   let depth = 0;\n36:   for (let j = i; j < text.length; j += 1) {\n37:     const ch = text[j];\n38:     if (ch === '{') depth += 1;\n39:     else if (ch === '}') {\n40:       depth -= 1;\n41:       if (depth === 0) return text.slice(i + 1, j);\n42:     }\n43:   }\n44:   return null;\n45: }\n46: \n47: function quotedStrings(segment) {\n48:   const out = [];\n49:   const re = /\"([^\"]*)\"|'([^']*)'/g;\n50:   let m;\n51:   while ((m = re.exec(segment)) !== null) out.push(m[1] !== undefined ? m[1] : m[2]);\n52:   return out;\n53: }\n54: \n55: // INTENT_SIGNALS = { \"KEY\": {\"weight\": N, \"keywords\": [\"a\",\"b\"]}, ... }\n56: function parseIntentSignals(body) {\n57:   const signals = {};\n58:   if (!body) return signals;\n59:   const entryRe = /[\"']([A-Z0-9_]+)[\"']\\s*:\\s*\\{([^}]*)\\}/g;\n60:   let m;\n61:   while ((m = entryRe.exec(body)) !== null) {\n62:     const key = m[1];\n63:     const inner = m[2];\n64:     const weightMatch = /[\"']weight[\"']\\s*:\\s*(\\d+(?:\\.\\d+)?)/.exec(inner);\n65:     const kwMatch = /[\"']keywords[\"']\\s*:\\s*\\[([^\\]]*)\\]/.exec(inner);\n66:     signals[key] = {\n67:       weight: weightMatch ? Number(weightMatch[1]) : 1,\n68:       keywords: kwMatch ? quotedStrings(kwMatch[1]).map((k) => k.toLowerCase()) : [],\n69:     };\n70:   }\n71:   return signals;\n72: }\n73: \n74: // RESOURCE_MAP = { \"KEY\": [\"path/a.md\", \"path/b.md\"], ... }\n75: function parseResourceMap(body) {\n76:   const map = {};\n77:   if (!body) return map;\n78:   const entryRe = /[\"']([A-Z0-9_]+)[\"']\\s*:\\s*\\[([^\\]]*)\\]/g;\n79:   let m;\n80:   while ((m = entryRe.exec(body)) !== null) map[m[1]] = quotedStrings(m[2]);\n81:   return map;\n82: }\n83: \n84: // DEFAULT_RESOURCE may be a single quoted path or a list of them. A skill's\n85: // always-loaded routing preamble (e.g. stack/phase detection plus the router\n86: // doc) is genuinely consulted on every route, so the replay seeds every result\n87: // with the whole set. Always returns an array; [] when absent.\n88: function parseDefaultResource(text) {\n89:   const listM = /DEFAULT_RESOURCE\\s*=\\s*\\[([\\s\\S]*?)\\]/.exec(text);\n90:   if (listM) {\n91:     return [...listM[1].matchAll(/[\"']([^\"']+)[\"']/g)].map((m) => m[1]);\n92:   }\n93:   const strM = /DEFAULT_RESOURCE\\s*=\\s*[\"']([^\"']+)[\"']/.exec(text);\n94:   return strM ? [strM[1]] : [];\n95: }\n96: \n97: // Some skills keep the authoritative router in a referenced doc (e.g.\n98: // references/smart_routing.md) rather than inlining it in SKILL.md. When the\n99: // inline dictionaries are absent we follow that pointer and parse the same\n100: // INTENT_SIGNALS / RESOURCE_MAP block from the referenced file. Inline always\n101: // wins; a skill with no inline block and no parseable referenced doc stays\n102: // unparseable, so a genuinely router-less skill is still reported as such.\n103: const ROUTER_REF_HINT = /(resource_map|intent_signals|intent_model|smart[ _-]?rout|routing logic)/i;\n104: \n105: function findReferencedRouterDoc(skillMdText, skillRoot) {\n106:   const pathRe = /(?:\\.\\/)?(references\\/[A-Za-z0-9_./-]+\\.md)/;\n107:   for (const line of skillMdText.split('\\n')) {\n108:     if (!ROUTER_REF_HINT.test(line)) continue;\n109:     const m = pathRe.exec(line);\n110:     if (m) {\n111:       const candidate = path.join(skillRoot, m[1]);\n112:       if (fs.existsSync(candidate)) return candidate;\n113:     }\n114:   }\n115:   // Convention fallback: a router doc at the well-known location.\n116:   const conventional = path.join(skillRoot, 'references', 'smart_routing.md');\n117:   return fs.existsSync(conventional) ? conventional : null;\n118: }\n119: \n120: function parseRouter(skillMdText, skillRoot) {\n121:   let intentSignals = parseIntentSignals(extractDictBody(skillMdText, 'INTENT_SIGNALS'));\n122:   let resourceMap = parseResourceMap(extractDictBody(skillMdText, 'RESOURCE_MAP'));\n123:   let defaultResource = parseDefaultResource(skillMdText);\n124:   let routerSource = 'inline';\n125: \n126:   const inlineEmpty = Object.keys(intentSignals).length === 0 && Object.keys(resourceMap).length === 0;\n127:   if (inlineEmpty && skillRoot) {\n128:     const refDoc = findReferencedRouterDoc(skillMdText, skillRoot);\n129:     if (refDoc) {\n130:       const refText = fs.readFileSync(refDoc, 'utf8');\n131:       const refSignals = parseIntentSignals(extractDictBody(refText, 'INTENT_SIGNALS'));\n132:       const refMap = parseResourceMap(extractDictBody(refText, 'RESOURCE_MAP'));\n133:       if (Object.keys(refSignals).length > 0 || Object.keys(refMap).length > 0) {\n134:         intentSignals = refSignals;\n135:         resourceMap = refMap;\n136:         defaultResource = defaultResource.length ? defaultResource : parseDefaultResource(refText);\n137:         routerSource = path.relative(skillRoot, refDoc);\n138:       }\n139:     }\n140:   }\n141: \n142:   const parseable = Object.keys(intentSignals).length > 0 || Object.keys(resourceMap).length > 0;\n143:   return { intentSignals, resourceMap, defaultResource, parseable, routerSource };\n144: }\n145: \n146: function scoreIntents(taskLower, intentSignals) {\n147:   const scores = [];\n148:   for (const [key, sig] of Object.entries(intentSignals)) {\n149:     let score = 0;\n150:     for (const kw of sig.keywords) {\n151:       if (kw && taskLower.includes(kw)) score += sig.weight;\n152:     }\n153:     if (score > 0) scores.push({ intent: key, score });\n154:   }\n155:   scores.sort((a, b) => b.score - a.score);\n156:   return scores;\n157: }\n158: \n159: function selectIntents(scores) {\n160:   if (scores.length === 0) return [];\n161:   const top = scores[0].score;\n162:   return scores.filter((s) => top - s.score <= AMBIGUITY_DELTA).map((s) => s.intent);\n163: }\n164: \n165: // Which surface a resource belongs to, by its on-disk path prefix. Webflow,\n166: // OpenCode, and Motion.dev resources live under their own folders, so the prefix\n167: // IS the surface. Everything else (universal refs, the detection/router preamble)\n168: // is surface-agnostic.\n169: const SURFACE_PREFIXES = {\n170:   WEBFLOW: ['references/webflow/', 'assets/webflow/'],\n171:   OPENCODE: ['references/opencode/', 'assets/opencode/'],\n172:   MOTION: ['references/motion_dev/', 'assets/motion_dev/'],\n173: };\n174: function resourceSurface(r) {\n175:   for (const [surface, prefixes] of Object.entries(SURFACE_PREFIXES)) {\n176:     if (prefixes.some((p) => r.startsWith(p))) return surface;\n177:   }\n178:   return 'UNIVERSAL';\n179: }\n180: // Detect the task's code surface from path / extension / marker signals, mirroring\n181: // the prose stack-detection contract: OpenCode system code wins, then Webflow\n182: // markers, else UNKNOWN. A task that names both is MIXED (cross-surface).\n183: function detectSurface(taskLower) {\n184:   const opencode = /\\.opencode\\/|\\bskill\\.md\\b|\\.cjs\\b|\\.mjs\\b|\\.tsx?\\b|\\.py\\b|\\.sh\\b|\\bspec-folder\\b|\\bargparse\\b|graph-metadata/.test(taskLower);\n185:   const webflow = /src\\/2_javascript|\\bwebflow\\b|\\.webflow\\b|--vw-/.test(taskLower);\n186:   if (opencode && webflow) return 'MIXED';\n187:   if (opencode) return 'OPENCODE';\n188:   if (webflow) return 'WEBFLOW';\n189:   return 'UNKNOWN';\n190: }\n191: // OpenCode-only language sub-detection (mirrors SKILL.md §2). A `.opencode/` task\n192: // is one language, so it needs only that language's guides — not every language\n193: // folder. Webflow deliberately has no sub-detection (a frontend task spans\n194: // css + html + js together).\n195: const OPENCODE_LANGUAGES = ['typescript', 'python', 'shell', 'config', 'javascript'];\n196: function detectOpencodeLanguage(taskLower) {\n197:   if (/\\.tsx?\\b/.test(taskLower)) return 'typescript';\n198:   if (/\\.py\\b|argparse/.test(taskLower)) return 'python';\n199:   if (/\\.sh\\b|set -euo|shellcheck/.test(taskLower)) return 'shell';\n200:   if (/\\.jsonc?\\b|graph-metadata|descriptor|spec-folder/.test(taskLower)) return 'config';\n201:   if (/\\.cjs\\b|\\.mjs\\b/.test(taskLower)) return 'javascript';\n202:   return null;\n203: }\n204: \n205: /**\n206:  * @returns {{ parseable: boolean, intents: string[], resources: string[],\n207:  *   missingResources: string[], scores: Array<{intent:string,score:number}>, surface?: string }}\n208:  */\n209: function routeSkillResources({ skillRoot, taskText }) {\n210:   const skillMd = readSkillMd(skillRoot);\n211:   const router = parseRouter(skillMd, skillRoot);\n212:   if (!router.parseable) {\n213:     return { parseable: false, intents: [], resources: [], missingResources: [], scores: [] };\n214:   }\n215:   const taskLower = String(taskText || '').toLowerCase();\n216:   const scores = scoreIntents(taskLower, router.intentSignals);\n217:   const intents = selectIntents(scores);\n218:   const resourceSet = new Set();\n219:   for (const r of router.defaultResource || []) resourceSet.add(r);\n220:   for (const intent of intents) {\n221:     for (const r of router.resourceMap[intent] || []) resourceSet.add(r);\n222:   }\n223:   let resources = [...resourceSet];\n224: \n225:   // Surface-aware slicing (only for skills with a per-surface resource layout,\n226:   // e.g. sk-code; a no-op for skills whose resources are all surface-agnostic).\n227:   // Load the universal tier + the Motion.dev overlay + only the DETECTED surface's\n228:   // slice, dropping the other surface's resources (the documented over-routing\n229:   // source). Assets are deferred — they are never the routing gold. A MIXED task\n230:   // keeps both surfaces (cross-surface non-starvation); UNKNOWN falls back to the\n231:   // universal + Motion tier only.\n232:   const mapResources = Object.values(router.resourceMap).flat();\n233:   const hasSurfaceLayout = mapResources.some((r) => r.startsWith('references/webflow/'))\n234:     && mapResources.some((r) => r.startsWith('references/opencode/'));\n235:   if (hasSurfaceLayout) {\n236:     const surface = detectSurface(taskLower);\n237:     // Within OpenCode, slice further to the detected language so a TypeScript task\n238:     // does not also pull the Python/shell/config guides. Non-language OpenCode\n239:     // folders (e.g. `shared/`) are always kept.\n240:     const ocLang = surface === 'OPENCODE' ? detectOpencodeLanguage(taskLower) : null;\n241:     resources = resources.filter((r) => {\n242:       if (r.startsWith('assets/')) return false;\n243:       const rs = resourceSurface(r);\n244:       if (rs === 'UNIVERSAL' || rs === 'MOTION') return true;\n245:       if (surface === 'MIXED') return true;\n246:       if (surface === 'UNKNOWN') return false;\n247:       if (rs !== surface) return false;\n248:       if (ocLang) {\n249:         const m = /^references\\/opencode\\/([^/]+)\\//.exec(r);\n250:         if (m && OPENCODE_LANGUAGES.includes(m[1]) && m[1] !== ocLang) return false;\n251:       }\n252:       return true;\n253:     });\n254:     const missingResources = resources.filter((r) => !fs.existsSync(path.join(skillRoot, r)));\n255:     return { parseable: true, intents, resources, missingResources, scores, surface };\n256:   }\n257: \n258:   const missingResources = resources.filter((r) => !fs.existsSync(path.join(skillRoot, r)));\n259:   return { parseable: true, intents, resources, missingResources, scores };\n260: }\n\n(Showing lines 1-260 of 278. Use offset=261 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"#!/usr/bin/env node\n'use strict';\n\n/**\n * router-replay.cjs — Mode A deterministic in-skill smart-router replay.\n *\n * The converged design needs the intra-skill router replayed deterministically\n * (zero leakage, CI-friendly) as the D1-intra signal and the D2 discovery proxy.\n * The router lives as INTENT_SIGNALS + RESOURCE_MAP inside a fenced block in the\n * target SKILL.md; it is documentation, not an importable module, so this script\n * extracts the dictionaries and reproduces the exact substring-scoring semantics:\n * lowercase the task, score each intent by whether each keyword is a substring,\n * keep intents within an ambiguity delta of the top score, then union the default\n * resource + RESOURCE_MAP[intent] for the selected intents.\n *\n * Exit: 0 on a successful replay (even with zero intents), 2 on unparseable router.\n */\n\nconst fs = require('fs');\nconst path = require('path');","truncated":true,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/router-replay.cjs","time":{"start":1780373171764,"end":1780373171773}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0fa816e44a8d16c4016a1e56b39ba88191b34b7aeefe0a591d"}},"id":"prt_e8682ae28001HhB4tC3Qrc64z7","sessionID":"ses_1797e0d22ffeXZXWmRS3UmbrPG","messageID":"msg_e86828e45001lFw5iqRCpN7qUL"}}
