{"type":"text","timestamp":1780373383214,"sessionID":"ses_1797e0d22ffeXZXWmRS3UmbrPG","part":{"id":"prt_e86851b2d0010VzPypZ2CYDFUP","messageID":"msg_e86850747001UcJlYuhDdgDB9n","sessionID":"ses_1797e0d22ffeXZXWmRS3UmbrPG","type":"text","text":"## Focus\nI chose lever 3: D4 measurement. It is the highest-value unexplored lever because the repository’s current post-remediation reports still do not score D4, while the only saved D4 artifact is a two-scenario, pre-remediation, “approximate” ablation. That makes any claim about routine-task usefulness currently UNKNOWN, and it also makes it hard to tell whether D3 gains are real user-cost reductions or scoring artifacts.\n\n## Actions Taken\n- Read `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/d4-ablation.cjs:5-15`, `:35-52`, `:58-80` to inspect the current D4 ablation design, formula, and contamination guard.\n- Read `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/grader/harness.cjs:4-20`, `:83-105`, `:213-248`, `:261-295` and `grader/prompts/system-grader.md:1-45` to verify what the grader actually scores.\n- Read `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/live-executor.cjs:35-52`, `:125-168` to inspect the live prompt and how stated resources, assets, and observed reads are parsed.\n- Read `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-benchmark.cjs:94-118`, `:130-131`, `:152-161`, `:254-275` to inspect D2/D3/D4 scoring and aggregation.\n- Read `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/run-skill-benchmark.cjs:15-17`, `:109-135`, `:169-175` and `executor-dispatch.cjs:36-74` to verify the benchmark execution path.\n- Read `.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-final/d4-ablation.json:1-29`, `live-final/skill-benchmark-report.json:18-39`, `:317-390`, and `live-remediated/skill-benchmark-report.json:18-39`, `:71-139`, `:305-371` to compare pre/post-remediation scoring evidence.\n- Read `.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/router-final/skill-benchmark-report.json:18-40`, `:193-304`, `:330-496`, `:687-730`, `:912-989` to inspect current router-mode scenario-level D2/D3/D4.\n- Read `.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/README.md:16-33`, `:73-101` to verify documented corpus, trace modes, and D4 artifact status.\n- Read `.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:43-49`, `:109-125`, `:189-198`, `:272-287`, `:291-322` to ground the usefulness target in the authored playbook.\n- Read `.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/02--language-sub-detection/004-opencode-typescript.md:14-39`, `005-opencode-python.md:14-39`, `006-opencode-shell.md:12-36`, and `007-opencode-config.md:12-36` to identify routine OPENCODE scenarios beyond LS-001.\n- Read `.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/01--surface-detection/002-opencode-detection.md:16-49`, `:80-91` to inspect a routine implementation-style outcome contract.\n- Read `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/browser-executor.cjs:4-16`, `:62-82`, `:88-113` to compare D4 with an executor that measures actual behavior.\n\n## Findings\n1. **f-i6-01: Post-remediation D4 is still unmeasured, so the routine-usefulness lift is UNKNOWN.** The live-remediated report has aggregate `79` but `D4.score: null` and `status: \"unscored-mode-a\"` (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-remediated/skill-benchmark-report.json:11-39`). The scorer hardcodes aggregate D4 as null/unscored for all reports (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-benchmark.cjs:254-264`). The only saved D4 artifact is the live-final ablation with `D4_aggregate: 49`, `scoredCount: 2`, `total: 2`, and `attribution: \"approximate\"` (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-final/d4-ablation.json:1-7`).\n\n2. **f-i6-02: The current D4 ablation is not a direct usefulness instrument; it reuses a hallucination grader.** `d4-ablation.cjs` calls `grader.gradeD4` on skill-on and skill-off text, then computes `0.5 + (onScore - offScore) / 2` (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/d4-ablation.cjs:47-52`). The grader system prompt says its job is “D4 Hallucination” and tells it not to score correctness, paths, or planning structure (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/grader/prompts/system-grader.md:3-4`, `:22-41`). Therefore LS-001’s stored `score: 0.435` means “skill-on had lower hallucination-grade output than skill-off,” not “the skill made the routine task less useful” (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-final/d4-ablation.json:10-17`).\n\n3. **f-i6-03: The live benchmark prompt prevents measuring what the model does with the slice.** The live executor reframes scenarios as “routing only,” says “do NOT edit files,” and asks for a fenced JSON block listing surface/resources/assets/agent (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/live-executor.cjs:35-52`). The playbook’s acceptance model, however, requires the AI’s user-visible outcome to be sound (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:43-49`, `:109-119`). Example: SD-002’s desired outcome is an actual TypeScript-aware fix plus verification evidence, while its routing test metadata says not to actually edit during routing tests (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/01--surface-detection/002-opencode-detection.md:46-49`, `:102-107`). Current D4 cannot see that outcome gap.\n\n4. **f-i6-04: Current live D3 is also partly a measurement artifact because it scores stated routing, not actual observed exploration cost.** `parseLiveResult` sets `observedResources` to the union of stated JSON `resources` and stated JSON `assets`, while `observedReads` are stored only under `raw` (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/live-executor.cjs:149-168`). `scoreScenario` then computes D3 from `routerResult.resources`, `routedCount`, and expected-resource waste (`.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-benchmark.cjs:102-118`). In live-remediated CS-001, the row scores D3 at `0.6667` from `routedCount: 15`, `wastedCount: 5`, but raw observed reads include broad `references/**/*.md`, `assets/**/*.md`, and `assets/motion_dev/snippets/*` globs (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-remediated/skill-benchmark-report.json:320-368`). That means the current D3 gain is real for stated first-slice routing, but not yet proven real for actual model exploration cost.\n\n5. **f-i6-05: The repository already has enough routine-task scenarios to fix D4’s n=2 problem without inventing a new corpus.** The playbook defines four OPENCODE language-sub-detection scenarios LS-001 through LS-004 (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:189-198`) and lists 24 total scenarios across seven categories (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:291-322`). LS-002 is a clean third routine candidate: “add a `--json-output` flag” to `skill_advisor.py`, expected `OPENCODE` + `PYTHON`, expected python/shared refs, expected python/universal assets, and no TypeScript/Shell/Config refs (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/02--language-sub-detection/005-opencode-python.md:14-39`). LS-003 and LS-004 provide shell/config follow-ups (`006-opencode-shell.md:12-36`, `007-opencode-config.md:12-36`).\n\n6. **f-i6-06: A build-ready D4-R instrument should be action-scored, not recall-scored.** The current playbook already defines the needed acceptance axes: exact prompt, advisor/surface/resource evidence, loaded refs/assets, agent dispatch, and user-visible outcome (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:75-84`, `:109-125`). The D4-R harness should run skill-on/skill-off in a no-write “produce a minimal patch plan or unified diff plus verification commands” mode, then score: task-action correctness, surface/language contamination, verification fit, and hallucinated symbol/path risk. This would measure whether the slice helps the model produce a better routine answer, while D2/D3 continue measuring routing recall/efficiency.\n\n7. **f-i6-07: The third routine scenario should be LS-002 first, not a synthetic new file.** LS-002 differs from LS-001 by language, target file, and expected reference family while staying routine and non-browser (`.opencode/skills/sk-code/manual_testing_playbook/02--language-sub-detection/005-opencode-python.md:16-39`). With current n=2, each scenario contributes 50 percentage points to the D4 mean; adding LS-002 drops that to 33.3 points per scenario. If the three scores were LS-001 `0.435`, CS-001 `0.55`, and a neutral LS-002 `0.50`, D4 would be `49.5`, effectively unchanged from the stored `49`; if LS-002 matched LS-001, D4 would fall to `47.3`. That shows the currently reported D4 magnitude is too sample-sensitive to guide remediation.\n\n## Implications for D3/D4\n- **D4 real-vs-artifact:** The stored `49` is mostly a measurement artifact for this question. It is sourced from a hallucination grader and two scenarios, not from a post-remediation routine-task usefulness run. The real post-remediation D4 is UNKNOWN until an action-scored D4-R suite is run.\n- **D3 real-vs-artifact:** The stated-resource D3 improvement is real inside the current scorer, but actual exploration-cost improvement is not proven. Live rows can still include broad `glob` reads that the D3 formula ignores.\n- **Expected D4 magnitude:** Adding LS-002 as a third routine probe will not by itself “lift” D4; it will make the estimate less volatile. The likely immediate gain is measurement honesty, not a score bump.\n- **Concrete next build lever:** Add D4-R as a separate reported dimension or D4 subscore: `D4_hallucination_delta` for the existing grader and `D4_task_outcome_delta` for routine usefulness. Do not collapse them into one number until both are populated.\n- **Routine suite proposal:** Run LS-001, LS-002, LS-003, LS-004, plus SD-002 in no-write patch-plan mode. Use CS-001 separately as a domain-pattern usefulness probe, not as evidence for routine OPENCODE usefulness.\n- **Pass condition for a real D4 lift:** Skill-on must improve task-action correctness or verification fit versus skill-off, without simply naming more expected resources and without increasing observed broad globs. If the only improvement is better path naming or fewer hallucinated symbols, classify it as benchmark-fidelity improvement, not routine usefulness.\n\n## What's still unexplored\n- Concern-level / phase-gated slicing is still the main unexplored routing lever after D4 measurement. It should inspect residual within-surface waste after language sub-slicing, especially Webflow implementation-vs-verification-vs-performance overlap.\n- The assets-scoring seam still needs an explicit scored-gold experiment, but prior findings already established the parser/scorer mismatch.\n- Gold↔map reconciliation remains needed for SD-001 and CS-001 D2 ceilings, but iteration 5 already separated at least one real intent-signal gap from one prompt-source artifact.\n- No repository evidence currently proves post-remediation D4 routine usefulness. UNKNOWN until the D4-R harness runs.\n\n```json\n{\"iteration\":6,\"focus\":\"D4 usefulness measurement instrument\",\"findings\":[{\"id\":\"f-i6-01\",\"label\":\"post-remediation D4 is still unmeasured, so routine-usefulness lift is UNKNOWN\"},{\"id\":\"f-i6-02\",\"label\":\"current D4 ablation reuses a hallucination grader, not a task-usefulness grader\"},{\"id\":\"f-i6-03\",\"label\":\"live benchmark prompt measures routing analysis only and prevents action-outcome scoring\"},{\"id\":\"f-i6-04\",\"label\":\"live D3 still scores stated resources while broad observed globs remain raw evidence only\"},{\"id\":\"f-i6-05\",\"label\":\"LS-002 is an existing third routine scenario candidate for D4-R\"}],\"newInfoRatio\":0.68,\"converged\":false,\"focusNext\":\"concern-level and phase-gated slicing for residual within-surface waste\"}\n```","time":{"start":1780373330733,"end":1780373383208},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0d0965e0c6d7a65e016a1e5752b6dc8191b5d3e2cd624d1b48","phase":"final_answer"}}}}
